The Nuremberg Code (1947)
Permissible Medical Experiments

The great weight of the evidence before us to effect that certain types of medical experiments on human beings, when kept within reasonably well-defined bounds, conform to the ethics of the medical profession generally. The protagonists of the practice of human experimentation justify their views on the basis that such experiments yield results for the good of society that are unprocurable by other methods or means of study. All agree, however, that certain basic principles must be observed in order to satisfy moral, ethical and legal concepts:
1. The voluntary consent of the human subject is absolutely essential. This means that the person involved should have legal capacity to give consent; should be so situated as to be able to exercise free power of choice, without the intervention of any element of force, fraud, deceit, duress, overreaching, or other ulterior form of constraint or coercion; and should have sufficient knowledge and comprehension of the elements of the subject matter involved as to enable him to make an understanding and enlightened decision. This latter element requires that before the acceptance of an affirmative decision by the experimental subject there should be made known to him the nature, duration, and purpose of the experiment; the method and means by which it is to be conducted; all inconveniences and hazards reasonably to be expected; and the effects upon his health or person which may possibly come from his participation in the experiment. The duty and responsibility for ascertaining the quality of the consent rests upon each individual who initiates, directs, or engages in the experiment. It is a personal duty and responsibility which may not be delegated to another with impunity.

As well as causing severe respiratory problems, there is mounting evidence COVID-19 causes abnormalities in blood clotting. Patients with severe COVID-19 infection appear to be at greater risk of developing blood clots in the veins and arteries.

Blood clots can occur deep in the veins of the leg (deep vein thrombosis) and can move to the lungs, causing a pulmonary embolism, which restricts blood flow and oxygen, and can be fatal.

Blood clots in arteries can cause heart attacks when they block blood supply to the heart, or strokes when they block oxygen supply to the brain.

So what is going on in the bodies of people with coronavirus? And what are clinicians doing to treat or prevent this complication?
What do these clots do?

Recent data from the Netherlands and France suggest that of the patients with coronavirus who are admitted to intensive care units (ICU), 30-70% develop blood clots in the deep veins of the legs, or in the lungs.

Around one in four coronavirus patients admitted to ICU will develop a pulmonary embolism.

These rates are much higher than we would usually see in patients requiring admission to ICU for reasons other than COVID-19.

You are missing two very important points that probably will clear up your confusion. 

Firstly, this isn‚Äôt about blood clots as you might get in the leg or arm, and that is quite common. Especially among the elderly. This is about a specific set of rare but very serious symptoms consisting of low platelet count, bleeding and blood clots in large blood vessels like brain stem or intestines. This combination of symptoms has shown up ten times more frequently then would normally be expected.

Secondly, if it wasn‚Äôt obvious enough from the first point, you can‚Äôt make a direct comparison between normal blood clots and the general population. For the reason that AstraZeneca didn‚Äôt provide documentation to the satisfaction of many countries for its effectiveness or efficacy among the elderly, most countries has used it for predominantly younger people, think front line health workers. So those that has been effected has mainly been young or younger women with no underlying conditions.

Whether there is a link or not still hasn‚Äôt been settled. It is still being investigated, and also says so explicitly in the EMA report. Although they do say that the benefits outweigh the risks, which might very well be true, and almost certainly is true in most countries on a population scale. Mass vaccinations are great, no doubt about it. 

But on an individual scale? Giving a healthy young women something that might give her very serious side effects as preventive medicine for a virus that she might never get, and would very likely only result in mild symptoms? Would a doctor under normal circumstances recommend or mandate that she be given the AstraZeneca vaccine based on an individual assessment? I am less certain. Or would a doctor tell her to wait until one of the others were available? Or to skip it completely? A precautionary principle is surely advisable. Which is also why a lot of countries are not giving the vaccine to the younger parts of the population. No reason to possibly risk some unnecessary deaths if you can avoid it. 

Also, on a side note. European politicians? No. Varies national medical agencies or vaccine regulators has either made recommendations, or had executive power to suspend the AstraZeneca vaccine. The notion that this is political is a myth fabricated in British media, most likely because the AstraZeneca vaccine has been used for political purposes there to such an extent that is surprising they haven‚Äôt started stamping the vials with Union Jacks.
